  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3177035521" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3177035521" />
    <a title="Nandakishore Mridula" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6237864-nandakishore-mridula"><img alt="Nandakishore Mridula" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1583648733p2/6237864.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3177035521?book_show_action=true">Feb 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nandakishore Mridula" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nandakishore Mridula" href="/user/show/6237864-nandakishore-mridula">Nandakishore Mridula</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3177035521" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8131594637071575299">I often find that engineers (who sometimes believe they are demigods), go berserk at the mention of Greta Thunberg. How dare this child who does not know anything about science, make such statements about climate change? How dare she tell the world to make a paradigm shift and stop using fossil fuels? And - this is the most heinous crime of all - how dare so many people follow her? If there is a problem because of carbon emission (and they are sure there isn&apos;t) engineers would find a way out of </span>
  <span id="freeText8131594637071575299" style="display:none">I often find that engineers (who sometimes believe they are demigods), go berserk at the mention of Greta Thunberg. How dare this child who does not know anything about science, make such statements about climate change? How dare she tell the world to make a paradigm shift and stop using fossil fuels? And - this is the most heinous crime of all - how dare so many people follow her? If there is a problem because of carbon emission (and they are sure there isn't) engineers would find a way out of it. Because engineers are qualified. Stupid laymen please shut up.<br /><br />I must say that I am a bit amused at this. Humans are so sure about their capability to control nature, of being "monarchs of all they survey", that even to suggest that they may be a wee bit not in control of their own destiny is to arouse fiery passions. (And this is especially true with us engineers because we are fed with the conceit that we "build" the nation.) But if you look at the evolutionary history of earth, homo sapiens has been present only for a tiny fraction of the time period. We are just a blip in the cosmic ocean of time...<br /><br />...a blip that may wink out at any moment.<br /><br />The older view evolution is that it was a slow, laborious process, proceeding at its own leisurely pace, with no jerks and bumps, one species morphing into another and the dead ends of evolution getting slowly weeded out. But we now know it's not so humdrum as that. Once in a while, there are massive upheavals which wipe out almost all the species on earth. We have had five of them so far (the most famous being the asteroid collision which wiped out the dinosaurs and made mammals the dominant species) and - this is the punchline - we may be living through the sixth.<br /><br />Elizabeth Kolbert has addressed the topic brilliantly in this book. In thirteen chapters, she takes us through the history of evolutionary theory and its development to the present form over the years: how Georges Cuvier discovered the concept of catastrophic extinction; how Charles Lyell disowned the concept but through his fossil research laid the springboard for Charles Darwin to launch his revolutionary theory of evolution; how the father-son pair of scientists Luis and Walter Alvarez convinced a reluctant scientific world about the asteroid that killed the dinosaurs and reshaped the earth. Then she goes on to talk about habitat destruction, ocean acidification, global warming and all those distressing subjects - about how humankind is slowly committing <i>seppukku</i>.<br /><br />What makes the book fascinating is its structure. Each of the thirteen chapters is a lesson in biology and the environment, a lesson in the history of the evolutionary theory, and an extremely entertaining account of a field trip she took with environmentalists/ scientists. These three strands are twined together so intricately and engagingly that the book just flows. You wouldn't for one second think that this is a book which discusses a matter which is - literally - life and death. And that is its greatest strength.<br /><br />(In Chapter V, Kolbert talks about Thomas Kuhn's <i>The Structure of Scientific Revolutions</i>. In it, the author argues that any data which threatens to upset the commonly held assumptions are always explained away or discounted until the crisis becomes so acute that someone finally has to call a spade a spade. It is called a "paradigm shift". That is what happened with extinction theory. And this is what is happening with climate change deniers, as I mentioned at the beginning of the review.)<br /><br />After painting a rather bleak picture for humankind's future, Kolbert gives us a ray of hope by saying that the same cognitive revolution which changed man into a such a destructive force also gave him the power to understand and tackle the consequences of his actions. So, even though we are in the middle of the sixth extinction, and we are largely responsible for it, we may be able to pull back from the precipice just in time.<br /><br />And if we aren't - well, it was an exciting time to live in.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8131594637071575299" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


