    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2806405941" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2806405941" />
    <a title="Henk" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76202320-henk"><img alt="Henk" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1557871304p2/76202320.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2806405941?book_show_action=true">Aug 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Henk" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Henk" href="/user/show/76202320-henk">Henk</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76202320-henk?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2806405941" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1375551320754544738"><b>Urgent, important and sobering. How we impact biodiversity, already since the stone age, and not for the better.</b><br/><i>Though it might be nice to imagine there once was a time when man lived in harmony with nature, it’s not clear if he ever did.</i><br/><br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/45840.Elizabeth_Kolbert' title='Elizabeth Kolbert' rel='nofollow noopener'>Elizabeth Kolbert</a> shows a love and awe for nature and biodiversity. She goes far and wide, from Iceland, to the South American rainforests, the fossil sites of North America and Paris museums, in the impressive journey recorded in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53089094.The_Sixth_Extinction_An_Unnatural_History' title='The Sixth Extinction An Unnatural History by Elizabeth Kolbert' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Sixth Extinction: An Unnatu</a></span>
  <span id="freeText1375551320754544738" style="display:none"><b>Urgent, important and sobering. How we impact biodiversity, already since the stone age, and not for the better.</b><br /><i>Though it might be nice to imagine there once was a time when man lived in harmony with nature, it’s not clear if he ever did.</i><br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/45840.Elizabeth_Kolbert" title="Elizabeth Kolbert" rel="nofollow noopener">Elizabeth Kolbert</a> shows a love and awe for nature and biodiversity. She goes far and wide, from Iceland, to the South American rainforests, the fossil sites of North America and Paris museums, in the impressive journey recorded in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53089094.The_Sixth_Extinction_An_Unnatural_History" title="The Sixth Extinction An Unnatural History by Elizabeth Kolbert" rel="nofollow noopener">The Sixth Extinction: An Unnatural History</a>. Not just physically but also the path of thinking about species, and our influence on them, is something she minutely traces. The book is well written and engaging, making the threshold to dive into the concept of speciation and extinction low.<br /><br />The revolutionary moment of evolution theory and archeology coinciding in the figures of Cuvier and Darwin is where the book starts of with in chapter 2. These scientists are pitted against an ancient believe that nature was unchangeable and perfect. And even the recent discovery in 1980 of the iridium layer around the world, marking the end of the age of dinosaurs, was still a necessary support for the idea that mass extinction of species could be real.<br /><br />Kolbert dives in a lot of interesting concepts, I never knew for instance that Anthropocene was a term popularized by a Dutch scientist! Another important one is the background extinction rate, estimated at maybe a species per 700-1.000 years going extinct normally. It is very clear that the current extinction rate of species which we are seeing, from massive dying of frogs, to coral bleaching and imported fungi killing bats, is far above this rate. We follow this story of human influence on biodiversity from a well known vantage point, the Industrial Revolution. The mass scale carelessness and cruelty of the destruction of the great auks, who from previously being protected by far of nesting grounds went to European ship food, feather supply and fuel because of their fat, is disheartening.<br /><br />In modern times we see that oceans are 30% more acidic than in 1800 and at current trajectory are expected to be at 150% at the end of the century. All captured in the deviously logaritmic pH scale change between 8 and 7.8. And with 7.8 being a tipping point that would wipe out over 30% of all marine life, ranging from mussels, oysters to clownfish.<br /><br />Even without the climate change, scientists show that the shredding of living environment of animals leads to a reduction in biodiversity, and especially that human intercontinental trade creates a new Pangea of interconnected ecosystems. Which invariably leads to niche species taking a hit or going extinct. <br /><br />And even before agriculture there are compelling indications that humanity started killing off megafauna: <i>He found that even a very small initial population of humans - a hundred or so individuals- could, over the course of a millennium or two, multiply sufficiently to account for pretty much all of the extinction in the record.</i><br />Not to mention the coincidental timing of the demise of our brethren the Neanderthals and the rise of homo sapiens. Not just murder would be the crime, but also rape: 2% to be 4% of modern day Asian and European DNA is traceable to Neanderthals.<br /><br />The Sixth Extinction is a sobering story of how the rise of humanity invariable seems to lead to a reduction of biodiversity through multi pronged influences of reduction of living environment, exploitation, climate change and import of new species. <br />Warning us, Kolbert ends with a quote from Stanford ecologist Paul Ehrlich, that I can only repeat: <i>in pushing other species to extinction, humanity is busy sawing off the limb on which it perches.</i><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1375551320754544738" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


