    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1261595945" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1261595945" />
    <a title="Caroline " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3236194-caroline"><img alt="Caroline " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576541068p2/3236194.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1261595945?book_show_action=true">Apr 22, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Caroline " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Caroline " href="/user/show/3236194-caroline">Caroline </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3236194-caroline?shelf=get-smart">get-smart</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3236194-caroline?shelf=lost-interest">lost-interest</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3236194-caroline?shelf=science">science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3236194-caroline?shelf=did-not-finish">did-not-finish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3236194-caroline?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3236194-caroline?shelf=pulitzer-prize-winner">pulitzer-prize-winner</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1261595945" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11680372948703446036">***NO SPOILERS***<br/><br/>(Full disclosure: book abandoned at page 173 [out of 269 pages].)<br/><br/>This book isn’t bad, and it’s definitely important--everyone should learn about the topic--but Kolbert isn’t an engaging writer, and engaging writing is crucial for such an involved topic. I was deceived because <i>The Sixth Extinction</i> starts out promising and my interest was piqued immediately; however, subsequent chapters go downhill. The first chapters discuss species now extinct, specifically the Panamanian golden</span>
  <span id="freeText11680372948703446036" style="display:none">***NO SPOILERS***<br /><br />(Full disclosure: book abandoned at page 173 [out of 269 pages].)<br /><br />This book isn’t bad, and it’s definitely important--everyone should learn about the topic--but Kolbert isn’t an engaging writer, and engaging writing is crucial for such an involved topic. I was deceived because <i>The Sixth Extinction</i> starts out promising and my interest was piqued immediately; however, subsequent chapters go downhill. The first chapters discuss species now extinct, specifically the Panamanian golden frog, the mastodon, and the great auk. When Kolbert deviated from her academic style and injected some feeling into her writing, as she did most successfully in the great auk chapter, I was instantly invested. <br /><br />The turn for the worse comes at about ⅓ of the way through, when Kolbert detailed how scientists grappled with explaining the dinosaur extinction. Specifically, she delved into the nitty-gritty of the controversy surrounding the asteroid-impact theory. This isn’t really so dull, but it doesn’t seem entirely relevant to the book’s premise, which is straightforward. (Straightforward enough that some quality articles on the sixth extinction can probably educate just as well, for much less time investment.) <br /><br />I consider <i>The Sixth Extinction</i> pretty science heavy mainly because Kolbert spent too much time on the finer points of geology (for instance, how much iridium is contained in certain rock) and fossils and chemical reactions; the list goes on. I wondered whether breaking down information as intricately as she did was truly necessary to see the larger picture, especially because she wrote this book to appeal to a wide range of readers, not just science geeks. Given how very important it is to get people to not just understand but <i>care</i> about what’s happening to the planet right now, it’s imperative that writers present pertinent information accessibly. There are ways to make science-writing appealing to the lay reader while still being thorough (see: author Sam Kean). The more of this book I read, though, the more I realized Kolbert doesn’t really have that knack, and I felt she forgot who her readers <i>really</i> are. <br /><br />Curiously, the book’s photos are in black-and-white (and are surprisingly boring photos at that). I consider the lack of color a drawback. If a lesser book such as <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/22668848.Aquarium" title="Aquarium by David Vann" rel="nofollow noopener">Aquarium</a> can feature color photos, surely this important book can. This is a smaller quibble, obviously, but I think top-notch, color photos could have bolstered Kolbert’s points or at least made the book more memorable. <br /><br />An endorsement on the back of the hardcover edition claims <i>The Sixth Extinction</i> “reads like a scientific thriller.” I find that amusing because a “scientific thriller” would be <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16213.The_Hot_Zone_The_Terrifying_True_Story_of_the_Origins_of_the_Ebola_Virus" title="The Hot Zone The Terrifying True Story of the Origins of the Ebola Virus by Richard Preston" rel="nofollow noopener">The Hot Zone: The Terrifying True Story of the Origins of the Ebola Virus</a>, and Kolbert’s style isn’t remotely like Preston’s. It would have been much better if it were, though. If any subject needs to be made exciting, it’s science (and perhaps history). <br /><br />I don’t suggest potential readers necessarily avoid this book, so this review is instead a forewarning. <i>The Sixth Extinction</i> isn’t a science book for the masses.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11680372948703446036" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


